<table  border=0 cellpadding=2 cellspacing=0 awidth=100%><a name=9674828011720></a><form action=http://eqdb.allakhazam.com/strategy/mrate.pl name=f9674828011720><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=classes.html?class=13&mid=9674828011720>Enchanters and healers - mana balancing</a> <a id=fs8 href=classes.html?class=13&mid=9674828011720#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=353><span id=Sage>Tehom</span></a>, <span id=Sage>Sage</span><br><span id=notbold>135 posts</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Mon, Aug 28th 1:13 PM 2000</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Decent<span id=notbold>[3.00]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>One of the most important roles an enchanter plays in a group is to reduce downtime. Some enchanters don't seem to understand that if they are oom while the party's lone healer is at FM, they have saved the group little time. Similarly, if they're at FM while a healer is oom, they have saved the group no time (as well as appearing as if they've done nothing). Ironically, while both cases hurt your party equally, you will generally only be considered a poor player in the latter case. In most dungeon groups, the best way to serve your party is to attempt to keep your mana at around the same level as your healer, casting less or more as situations demand in order to eliminate unnecessary downtimes. For example, if you're consistently running low on mana compared to healers, it's sometimes necessary to assume a very spartan function of only mezzing, and nothing else. If, on the other hand, you have more mana than the cleric per fight, slowing npcs (if there is no shaman in the group, or you are in the level range where tepid is better than the insects spell they have) is one of the more efficient ways to conserve healer mana, followed by charming, then less efficient methods such as casting damaging spells, chain-stunning, pseudo-healing with runes/beserker line, or premature renewal of buffs. Just remember to keep pestering your healer to tell you how much mana he has, be aware when you or he will have to renew expensive buffs, and be able to adapt quickly to avoid 5 minute downtimes.<br>&nbsp;<br></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 >&nbsp;</td><td align=right valign=bottom>
	   <span style='font-weight: normal; font-size: 9px;'>[<a href=#top>Top</a>]</span></tr>
	   </form></table><ul>
