<table  border=0 cellpadding=2 cellspacing=0 awidth=100%><a name=96712931311306></a><form action=http://eqdb.allakhazam.com/strategy/mrate.pl name=f96712931311306><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=classes.html?class=13&mid=96712931311306>Fear in dungeons...</a> <a id=fs8 href=classes.html?class=13&mid=96712931311306#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=353><span id=Sage>Tehom</span></a>, <span id=Sage>Sage</span><br><span id=notbold>135 posts</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Thu, Aug 24th 11:01 AM 2000</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Decent<span id=notbold>[3.40]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>Fear is an underutilized spells in dungeons. Against some higher level opponents, you may find your group taking quite a beating from the point where the npc hits around 30% health to before they die - at this point, if the npc were running and snared, they are effectively dead. It's in some of these rare situations that I quickly swap in fear, and often save the cleric some decent amount of mana. You need to be fairly certain, however, that the npc is snared - otherwise you have an instant runner, and your group may be fairly irked with you. This can even apply before the npc reaches the "stopped from snare" point, provided you know the pathing extremely well, and are absolutely certain you won't get any adds from having it move a little.<br>&nbsp;<br></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 >&nbsp;</td><td align=right valign=bottom>
	   <span style='font-weight: normal; font-size: 9px;'>[<a href=#top>Top</a>]</span></tr>
	   </form></table><ul>
