<table  border=0 cellpadding=2 cellspacing=0 awidth=100%><a name=96725953925773></a><form action=http://eqdb.allakhazam.com/strategy/mrate.pl name=f96725953925773><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=classes.html?class=13&mid=96725953925773>RE: Fear in dungeons...</a> <a id=fs8 href=classes.html?class=13&mid=96725953925773#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=508><span id= >Sobur</span></a>, <span id= > </span><br><span id=notbold>6 posts</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Fri, Aug 25th 11:12 PM 2000</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Excellent<span id=notbold>[4.66]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>I would rather not use Fear in a dungeon. The risk is too great that the snare can run out before the fear and you have a major mess to deal with. Or you have a different target than the snare caster. Or a multitude of other equally nasty possibilities. I instead will help my group by using another under used spell, Whirl 'til you hurl. Yes I know that it isn't as good as it used to be, BUT, it gives your tank, pet, cleric, time to 1- do damage without taking any, 2- get a timely heal or bandage in, 3- if they are casters, get a spell off without being inturrupted. Any of those is a big plus and will save you from having to chase. If no dots were cast and you have a well trained group and a controllable pet mes is an even better choice if you need a quick breather... but anything that works is good. The best thing anyone can do is get a willing group to try different tactics to see what is best in different situations. Experience is always the best teacher....<br>&nbsp;<br>Sobur<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;Dying with style, in a zone near you...</td></tr>
