<table  border=0 cellpadding=2 cellspacing=0 awidth=100%><a name=96710584225795></a><form action=http://eqdb.allakhazam.com/strategy/mrate.pl name=f96710584225795><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=classes.html?class=13&mid=96710584225795>Soloing and Skills</a> <a id=fs8 href=classes.html?class=13&mid=96710584225795#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <span id= >Anonymous</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Thu, Aug 24th 4:30 AM 2000</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Default<span id=notbold>[2.00]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>Well I'm up to 7th level, and soling most of the time.<br><br>Normally I'll buff myself (armour, strength, blurr) and my pet (strength).<br>Weakness or enfeeblement is a very nice pull spell (stand somewhere safe-ish and<br>zap the monster.&nbsp;&nbsp;It'll come to you.).  Join in melee with your pet (gets defense and<br>attack skills up), maybe a DD spell when the monster turns to run so you don't have<br>to chase it.  Loot corpse and sell/use the goodies.  Mainly blue monsters, although white<br>is sometimes possible (but depends on the mob).<br><br>After going up a level try this:  Find a lake or river, get a fishing rod handy.  Cast all your<br>buff and divination spells on yourself.  Conjure a pet.  Dismiss the lot and repeat until<br>you are out of mana.  Meditate, fish and practice sense direction.  Repeat until bored or<br>skills maxed.  Sell (or use) fish, sell sandals and daggers, put fish scales in bank, go find something to kill.  I also always keep myself under an illusion (mainly for the practice -<br>sneeking into Neriak to get an enchant silver spell is going to be tricky).  Invisability is<br>very useful for moving through areas quickly (but experiment to learn when it fails).  Greater Felwithe and Butcherblock are good areas at my level (but stay away from the orcs).  WC and<br>NoRo might be ok as well.<br><br>Pick up some trade skills - tailoring, cooking, brewing.  With all skills leave the purchase<br>until as late as you can - your initial skill is equal to your level.  If you can't afford to be a jeweler, don't buy the skill.  Wait until you're 10th level and the first point you invest will<br>get you a skill of 10.  I'm not going to get research util 26th level (when the skill 26 I get<br>from my first point is under the skill cap - buying it at 16th level throws away 25 free points).<br><br>Yenedarrya<br>&nbsp;<br> </td></tr>
